@node WHATISIT "What LibMon actually Is"

	A Brief History of the Development of LibVer/LibMan/LibMon
	----------------------------------------------------------

	Not so long ago, I was getting into programming in a big way.  I
	quite enjoy living off the thought "If a program doesn't do what
	you want it to, write one that does!".  In particular, I had
	problems when it came to using libraries.  I have so many of
	them that I can't fit all onto one floppy, much less one that has
	to share it's space with other software.  My problems came to a 
	head when I got the AmigaGuide software.  Where was I going to fit
	a 60K library?  In frustration, I wrote a short and dirty assembly
	language program that opened and closed a specified library, thus
	loading it into memory.  It worked.
	
	LibMon is the decendent of that program, incorperating many ideas
	that I had but couldn't do in assembly.  Early versions (LibMan)
	were written in E.  Although a good language, it's not really
	suitable for systems programming, so I've ported it into C.
	
	The compiler I've used is DICE, but I havn't used any 
	compliler-specific code, so it should re-compile on any ANSI 
	compiler (gcc, vbcc, etc), but I havn't tried it (some feedback 
	in this area would be nice).  This change came about because 
	the old versions were crashing high end 4000s.
	
@{" Back to Contents " LINK MAIN}
	
@endnode


@node USAGE "Using the Library Monitor"

Description:

	Phew! Now, exactly what does LibMon do?
	LibMon can load, list or flush libraries.  It can be used
	individually, or applied to all libraries in LIBS: or memory.
	LibMon requires OS2 (v36) or above.
	
Input:
	LibMon uses the ReadArgs template to provide an easy interface.
	The template looks like this:
	
		LIBS=LIBNAMES/M,A=ALL/S,L=LIST/S,F=FLUSH/S
	
	The elements in the template are as follows:
	LIBNAMES:	One or more library names to be affected.
	ALL:		Affects all libraries.
	LIST:		List library(s).
	FLUSH:		Flush libraries(s).
	
	The LIST and FLUSH commands are mutually exclusive (cannot be used
	at the same time), as are the LIBNAMES and ALL fields.  An invalid
	combination will cause the Usage message ot be displayed.

	This argument chart may come in useful.
	
	Switch		Without LIBNAMES	With LIBNAMES
	DEFAULT		* N/A - Usage		Load LIBNAMES
	ALL		Load All Libraries	* N/A - Usage
	LIST		List All Libraries	List LIBNAMES
	FLUSH		Flush All Libraries	Flush LIBNAMES
	ALL LIST	List All Libraries	* N/N - Usage
	LIST FLUSH	* N/A - Usage		* N/A - Usage
	ALL LIST FLUSH	* N/A - Usage		* N/A - Usage
	
Output:
	There are four different types of output for LibMon:
	
	Usage		Usage information displayed.
	Load and Flush	Both display the name, and the version.revision
			of the libraries.
	List		Displays the name, version.revision, priority,
			location and open count of the libraries.

Errors:
	If LibMon can't perform a task, then it will inform you, and
	will continue with the next item, except if LIBS: cannot be
	locked (This will not be a problem for most people), or if you 
	run out of memory, in which case the program will end.
	
	Well, that's about it.  One final note: You can break (ctrl-c)
	during loading and listing of libraries.  Have fun!

@endnode


@node HISTORY "The History of Library Monititor"

	The History of Library Monititor
	--------------------------------
	
	V1.00 (1 August 1996)
		- Initial Release as Library Manager (LibMan).
	
	
	V1.10 (11 August 1996)
		- LIST output changed: Address is now 8-Char (32 bit),
		  Priority is signed(+/-).
		- Basically the entire way that LISTing and FLUSHing
		  occurs had been altered.  Much safer, and hopefully
		  no more chashes on A4000's ;)  Look at the source,
		  if you like.
		- Changed minimum OS from 37 (2.04) to 36 (2.0)
		- Fully re-entrant i.e. "Resident Libman" works.
	
	
	V1.25 (4 Dec 1996)
		- Renamed Library Monitor (LibMon).
		- Completely rewritten, from stratch, in ANSI C with
		  Amiga extensions (ie no compiler-specific code).
		- Added multiple library names on the command line.
		- An extra LIST field - Open Count.
	
	V2.10 (28th October 1997)
		- Another rewrite! Based on V1.25, still in ANSI C.
		- LibMon now uses System Lists and exec functions
		  (AddTail(), FindName(), etc).  Should be faster.
		- Re-wrote the documents in AmigaGuide format, fixing
		  several grammatical 'accidents' along the way.
		- Fixed stupid typo in History section
		  (4 Dev 1996 => 4 Dec 1996)
		- I split up the source code into several modules and 
		  wrote a DMakeFile for it (My general programming style
		  has changed a bit over the past year as I get better
		  at it).

	
	Plans for the Future
	--------------------
	
	Well, nothing at the moment.  I am almost totally sick of this
	program.  But if I do decide to develope it further, I'll make
	it a true monitor, with a simple internal shell or something.
	Maybe I could even make it a Workbench commodity, with Hotkeys
	and Popup window with all the functions available on screen, or 
	even better, add the functions to the Tools menu!  That would
	be really cool!
	
